# Azure POC ‚Äî CI/CD Pipeline

A GitHub Actions CI/CD pipeline that builds, scans, and deploys a Node.js containerised application to **Azure Container Apps** using **Terraform** and **OIDC authentication** (no stored credentials).

---

## Architecture Overview

```
GitHub Actions
      ‚îÇ
      ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ OIDC ‚Üí Azure (no secrets)
      ‚îÇ
      ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ Build Docker Image
      ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ Scan with Trivy
      ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ Push to Azure Container Registry (ACR)
      ‚îÇ
      ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ Terraform Apply
            ‚îÇ
            ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ Azure Container Apps
                  ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ Managed Identity ‚Üí ACR Pull
                  ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ Key Vault integration
                  ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ Multiple revision mode
                  ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ Auto-rollback via readiness probe
```

---

## Prerequisites

- Azure subscription
- Azure Container Registry (ACR)
- Azure Container Apps environment
- Azure Key Vault
- Terraform state backend (Azure Storage Account)
- GitHub repository

---

## Secrets Configuration

Add the following secrets to your GitHub repository under **Settings ‚Üí Secrets and variables ‚Üí Actions**:

| Secret | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| `AZURE_CLIENT_ID` | Service principal / app registration client ID (used for OIDC) |
| `AZURE_TENANT_ID` | Azure Active Directory tenant ID |
| `AZURE_SUBSCRIPTION_ID` | Azure subscription ID |
| `ACR_NAME` | Azure Container Registry name (e.g. `myregistry`) |
| `ACR_LOGIN_SERVER` | ACR login server (e.g. `myregistry.azurecr.io`) |
| `TF_STORAGE_ACCOUNT` | Storage account name for Terraform remote state |
| `CONTAINER_APP_NAME` | Container App name (e.g. `poc-app-dev`) |
| `RESOURCE_GROUP` | Azure resource group name |
| `ENVIRONMENT` | Environment name (e.g. `dev`) |

---

## OIDC Setup

This pipeline uses OpenID Connect ‚Äî no Azure credentials are stored as GitHub secrets.

### 1. Create an App Registration in Azure

```bash
az ad app create --display-name "github-actions-poc"
az ad sp create --id <app-id>
```

### 2. Add Federated Credential

In Azure Portal ‚Üí App Registration ‚Üí Certificates & secrets ‚Üí Federated credentials:

```
Organisation:  <your-github-org>
Repository:    <your-repo>
Entity:        Branch
Branch:        main
```

Or via CLI:

```bash
az ad app federated-credential create \
  --id <app-id> \
  --parameters '{
    "name": "github-main",
    "issuer": "https://token.actions.githubusercontent.com",
    "subject": "repo:<org>/<repo>:ref:refs/heads/main",
    "audiences": ["api://AzureADTokenExchange"]
  }'
```

### 3. Assign Roles

```bash
# Contributor on resource group
az role assignment create \
  --assignee <client-id> \
  --role Contributor \
  --scope /subscriptions/<sub-id>/resourceGroups/<rg>

# User Access Administrator on ACR (needed to assign AcrPull to Container App)
az role assignment create \
  --assignee <client-id> \
  --role "User Access Administrator" \
  --scope /subscriptions/<sub-id>/resourceGroups/<rg>/providers/Microsoft.ContainerRegistry/registries/<acr-name>
```

---

## Terraform Variables

| Variable | Description |
|----------|-------------|
| `image_tag` | Docker image tag (commit SHA) |
| `revision_number` | GitHub Actions run number ‚Äî used in revision name |
| `environment` | Deployment environment (`dev`, `staging`, `prod`) |
| `resource_group_name` | Azure resource group |
| `acr_login_server` | ACR login server URL |
| `min_replicas` | Minimum Container App replicas |
| `max_replicas` | Maximum Container App replicas |
| `container_app_cpu` | CPU allocation per replica |
| `container_app_memory` | Memory allocation per replica |
| `key_vault_uri` | Key Vault URI for secret injection |
| `deployer_object_id` | Object ID of the OIDC service principal |

---

## Pipeline Flow

```
Checkout code
      ‚Üì
Azure Login (OIDC)
      ‚Üì
Terraform Init
      ‚Üì
Build Docker Image
      ‚Üì
Trivy Scan (CRITICAL + HIGH)
      ‚Üì
Upload SARIF to GitHub Security tab
      ‚Üì
Push image to ACR  ‚Üê image exists in ACR from here
      ‚Üì
Terraform Apply
  -var image_tag=<sha>
  -var revision_number=<run_number>
      ‚Üì
Verify revision health (poll 3 mins)
      ‚Üì
Deactivate old revisions (keep last 2)
      ‚Üì
Summary
```

---

## Revision Naming

Each deployment creates one revision named:

```
poc-app-dev--v<run_number>-<short_sha>

Examples:
  poc-app-dev--v5-f0af0d1
  poc-app-dev--v6-19a86dd
```

| Part | Source | Example |
|------|--------|---------|
| `v5` | `github.run_number` ‚Äî increments every run | `v5` |
| `f0af0d1` | First 7 chars of `github.sha` | `f0af0d1` |

---

## Auto-Rollback

Azure Container Apps handles rollback automatically via the **readiness probe**:

```
New revision deployed (v6-19a86dd)
        ‚Üì
Readiness probe hits GET /health:3000
        ‚Üì
    PASS ‚úÖ                  FAIL ‚ùå
        ‚Üì                        ‚Üì
Traffic shifts to v6      Traffic stays on v5
v5 kept as rollback       v6 stays in failed state
Pipeline green ‚úÖ          Pipeline red ‚ùå
```

### Readiness Probe Configuration

```hcl
readiness_probe {
  transport               = "HTTP"
  path                    = "/health"
  port                    = 3000
  interval_seconds        = 10
  failure_count_threshold = 3
  success_count_threshold = 1
}
```

### Health Check Endpoint

Your application must expose `GET /health` on port `3000` returning HTTP `200`.

Example (Node.js / Express):

```javascript
app.get('/health', (req, res) => {
  res.status(200).json({ status: 'ok' });
});
```

---

## Manual Rollback

If you need to manually shift traffic back to the previous revision:

```bash
# List active revisions
az containerapp revision list \
  --name poc-app-dev \
  --resource-group <rg> \
  --query "[?properties.active==true].{Revision:name, Traffic:properties.trafficWeight}" \
  -o table

# Shift 100% traffic to previous revision
az containerapp ingress traffic set \
  --name poc-app-dev \
  --resource-group <rg> \
  --revision-weight poc-app-dev--v5-f0af0d1=100
```

---

## Revision Retention

The pipeline keeps the **last 2 active revisions**:

```
v4-abc1234  ‚Üê deactivated ‚úÖ (older than last 2)
v5-f0af0d1  ‚Üê kept ‚Äî rollback target
v6-19a86dd  ‚Üê kept ‚Äî current, 100% traffic
```

This gives you one rollback target without accumulating idle revisions that consume resources.

---

## ACR Authentication

The Container App uses a **System-Assigned Managed Identity** to pull images from ACR ‚Äî no credentials required.

```hcl
identity {
  type = "SystemAssigned"
}

registry {
  server   = var.acr_login_server
  identity = "System"
}
```

Terraform assigns the `AcrPull` role to the Container App's identity automatically:

```hcl
resource "azurerm_role_assignment" "container_app_acr_pull" {
  scope                = var.acr_id
  role_definition_name = "AcrPull"
  principal_id         = azurerm_container_app.poc.identity[0].principal_id
}
```

---

## Security Scanning

Trivy scans the image before it is pushed to ACR:

- **Table output** ‚Äî visible in the Actions log
- **SARIF output** ‚Äî uploaded to GitHub Security tab (Code scanning alerts)
- `exit-code: "0"` ‚Äî pipeline does not fail on vulnerabilities (adjust to `"1"` to enforce blocking)

To enforce blocking on CRITICAL vulnerabilities:

```yaml
- name: Trivy ‚Äî Scan Image
  uses: aquasecurity/trivy-action@master
  with:
    exit-code: "1"         # change from "0" to "1"
    severity: "CRITICAL"
```

